{"cursor":"2492","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'' Afghan carpets.]] An 'Afghan rug' (or 'Afghan carpet' ) is a\ntype of handwoven floor-covering textile traditionally made in Afghanistan. [http://www.pajhwok.com/viewstory.asp?lng=eng&id=49487 Afghan\nrugs sell like hot cakes] Many of the Afghan rugs are also woven by Afghan\nrefugees who reside in Pakistan and Iran. [http://afghanrugs.com/ Afghan\nrugs] In any case, Afghan rugs are genuine, charming â and usually\nphenomenally inexpensive. One of the most exotic and distinctive of all oriental\nrugs is the [[Shindand]] or [[Adraskan]] (named after local Afghan towns), woven\nin the Herat area, in western Afghanistan. Strangely elongated human and animal\nfigures are their signature look. The carpet can be sold across Afghanistan with\nthe most based in Mazar-e Shariff.\n\nAnother staple of Afghanistan is Baluchi rugs, most notably Baluchi prayer rugs.\nThey are made by Afghanistan's Baloch people, also in the south-western part of\nthe country. Most of the weavers in Afghanistan are the Ersari Turkmen, but\nother smaller groups such as Chub Bash and Kizil Ayaks are also in the line of\nweaving rugs. In addition, Uzbeks, Kyrgyz, Kazakhs, and Arabs label their rugs\naccording to their ethnic group. \"Afghan carpet.\" EncyclopÃ¦dia\nBritannica. 2009. EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica Online. 04 Nov. 2009 . See picture on the right margin.\n\nVarious vegetable and other natural dyes are used to produce the rich colors.\nThe rugs are mostly of medium sizes. Many patterns and colors are used, but the\ntraditional and most typical is that of the octagonal elephant's foot (Bukhara)\nprint, often with a red background. The weavers also produce other trappings of\nthe nomadic lifestyle, including tent bags and ceremonial pieces.\n\n print.]]\n","linknr":239,"url":"Afghan_carpet","recorded":1375055926,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Afghan_rug&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Afghan_rug&action=edit","//bits.wikime